**Special Note:  USENIX Conference Meeting Space

Some conference attendees have asked about
conference accommodations.  Here is how USENIX
conference hotels are chosen:  The week-long
USENIX conference places a heavy demand on
meeting space.  To offset the cost of renting
meeting space, USENIX guarantees to a hotel (or
hotels) a minimum number of sleeping rooms rented
by attendees.  In exchange, the hotel provides
meeting space and other services at no direct cost
to USENIX.  Such agreements are complicated and,
because the number of facilities in the U.S. which
can accommodate a USENIX conference is limited,
we typically sign hotel contracts five (!) years in
advance.  These contracts contain penalty clauses
(sometimes exceeding $50,000) if the room block
guarantee is unmet.  Moreover, groups that can't
live up to their contracts find in the future they
have trouble renting space or may have to pay a
higher rate.

There are a couple of consequences to these
arrangements.  One is that it is important when
making your reservation that you state you are
attending the USENIX Conference and that you pay
the USENIX rate, so we get credit towards fulfilling
our room block commitment.  (If you use a
corporation's discount rate, it will not count as a
credit towards the USENIX commitment.).  Another
is that widespread defection from our headquarters
hotel will lead to higher registration fees for
everybody.

We try to choose sites that offer less expensive
room rates or, at least, less expensive hotels
nearby.  Usenet facilitates room sharing; check
comp.org.usenix.roomshare for this.

